com.ibm.team.repository.common.query.ast

Interface IStringField

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IField, IFilterElement, ISelectionElement, IString

    public interface IStringField
extends IField, IString
    Defines the query model for all string attributes. IStringField instances can be acquired by traversing to a string attribute from a from a query model root.

      • _in

        IPredicate _in(IString[] a)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the value of this query element is equal to one of the query elements in the list.

        NOTE: On some databases (e.g. DB2) string equality comparison behaves as if the shorter of the two strings were first padded on the right to with spaces until it is the same length as the longer string. This means, for example, that "abc" may compare equal to "abc ". If this is not acceptable then additional or different filtering may be required.

        Parameters:
        a - the list of values to compare this elment to
        Returns:
        a predicate that can be used in query filters

      • _inLargeList

        IPredicate _inLargeList(IInListValueSource<java.lang.String> inputSource)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the value of this query element is equal to one of the literal values.

        Generally, a database provider has limits to the number of input parameters that can be passed into a query. This API can be used by the caller when they know up front that the collection of values could be large enough such that it would exceed the platform limits. The query service will use an alternate path for query execution which may be slower than a typical in query, thus this should be used sparingly. Even with this API, callers should take precautions to ensure that the total number of input values is bounded. The server will be defensive and fail in the case of excessively large collections.

        The iterator idiom is used to allow for streaming large collections without having to load all elements into memory.

        Note: This is only supported server-side. Clients should not expect to use this interface to construct an AST query client-side and send it over the wire via an RPC call. It is expected that the caller will be a server side service that is also streaming the values, either from an http request stream or from the result of another query.
        On some databases (e.g. DB2) string equality comparison behaves as if the shorter of the two strings were first padded on the right to with spaces until it is the same length as the longer string. This means, for example, that "abc" may compare equal to "abc ". If this is not acceptable then additional or different filtering may be required.

        Parameters:
        inputSource - an input source that supplies the parameter values to compare this element to
        Returns:
        a predicate that can be used in query filters
        Since:
        0.7

      • _like

        IPredicate _like(IString pattern)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the string value of this element matches the value of the pattern. The pattern can contain two special characters '%' and '_'. All '%' characters match 0 or more patterns in the value and all '_' characters match exactly one character in the value. All other characters in the pattern must match the value exactly.
        Parameters:
        pattern - the value to compare the query element to
        Returns:
        a predicate that can be used in query filters

      • _like

        IPredicate _like(IString pattern,
                 char escape)
        Returns a predicate that evaluates to true when the string value of this element matches the value of the pattern. The pattern can contain two special characters '%' and '_'. All '%' characters match 0 or more patterns in the value and all '_' characters match exactly one character in the value. All other characters in the pattern must match the value exactly.
        Parameters:
        pattern - the value to compare the query element to
        escape - the character used to escape the '_' and '%' characters. If the pattern contains an escape character followed by a character that is not '_', '%', or the escape character, the query will result in an error.
        Returns:
        a predicate that can be used in query filters
